Food blamed for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapidly rising food prices.
Inflation in the 13 countries of the euro zone was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was registered, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts put the figure at just 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the Federal Reserve of the United States, the United Kingdom, and Canada, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered its benchmark interest rate, which it believes would encourage the creation of an inflationary spiral by rising commodity prices and a slight drop in unemployment.
The ECB aims to keep inflation below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in a quandary: inflation must be "coordinated" in order to rule out the need for further action.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the eurozone was due to the rise in food and energy prices.
Wheat prices rose 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also hit a record high since 1973.
The price of cooking oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
The world price of crude oil has risen 52 percent this year - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1% to 2.5% in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts expect inflation to reach 3 percent in the next 3-4 months, but put the average annual rate at 2.1 percent.
Experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup finds government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers grew significantly by early December, with the party having its largest base camp for the first time since 2002, while support for the Socialists reached an all-time low of 13%, according to Gallup.
Among party-loyal voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) oppose a fifth (20 percent) support for the MSZP.
According to the survey, the MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry barrier: they reach two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one per cent in both camps.
Compared to the last low point, the general economic mood has deteriorated further - the share of those who say the country's economic situation is "decidedly bad" has never been this high (41%), while a further 46% consider it "pretty bad."
After more hopeful prospects in the spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about the change in their financial situation.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate further; only a tenth expect it to improve.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents - an all-time high - rated the prime minister's job "more bad than right."
Thirteen percent of respondents have great confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the share of those in favour of Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Some 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% who do not trust the Fidesz leader.
One of the indicators of the political mood is the number of those who believe that dissatisfaction with the prime minister can be controlled even without a change of government.
Whereas after the riots last October, 35% of the electorate voted for the government and the head of government to remain, today this figure stands at only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 per cent said they would "certainly" vote and a further 20 per cent would "probably" vote.
By way of comparison, if the parliamentary elections were held this Sunday, only 55% would "certainly" go to the polls, and a further 15% consider their participation "likely." Given these trends, the outcome of the referendum would be predictable.
74% would vote against tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital day allowance.
Applied to the group of people who "certainly" took part in the referendum, the proportion opposed to tuition, practice and hospital fees would be 81, 84 and 89 per cent respectively.
Auchan most expensive, Tesco increases by almost a fifth
Hypermarkets in the Buda trade area have maintained the average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that there was no increase in VAT this year.
Article from Napi Gazdaság
In the trade triangle of Buda, the price of the usual Napi Christmas basket has increased by 16 percent this year, but price increases of more than 1,000 HUF have been registered in all hypermarkets.
After prices in the food markets "galloped away" last December, the percentage of inflation has not been drastic, compared with the already high, earlier starting level.
However, it certainly has a deterrent effect on consumers that what they paid well below 9,000 HUF last year is not even available for 10,000 HUF this year.
The price of the "Napi" basket exceeded the magic 10,000 HUF limit by at least 91 HUF in the markets examined.
The highest price was 10.573 HUF.
(In 6800 the price was 6.800 HUF.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at the same level as last year, but prices for turkey breast fillets, nuts and poppy seeds rose sharply.
Prices for flour and bread corresponded to the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary, but Auchan had 1kg bread for 139 forints.
There was no fall in the price of the product to below 200 forints due to competition.
Also surprising was the price of a two litre Coca-Cola deposit bottle of less than 200 HUF, so the drink including the deposit cost only 257 HUF.
Nevertheless, in the Napi basket comparison this year, Auchan was the most expensive, and Cora the cheapest.
Our calculations have shown that Cora's "Napi" basket prices have increased by 15 per cent compared to Christmas prices last year, while Tesco and Auchan have both increased by 18 per cent.
The difference between last year's cheapest basket and this year's most expensive was 12%, while the increase between last year's cheapest basket and this year's most expensive was 21%.
The average price increase was 1.480,00 HUF.
The average price increase in the previous year was still 1,206.00 Forints, but the VAT increase was noticeable in the prices at last Christmas.
It is precisely this process that has hit retail hard: it seems that department stores have been unable to decide which price range to apply to individual articles, as the impact of the price increase on consumer behaviour has been incalculable.
(If the trader does not plan the circulation speed of a product well, he may lose substantial profits in the price range, which depends on traffic intensity.)
Due to VAT, the inflation of the "Napi" basket last year was so radical that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 Forints, whereas the price difference for the cheapest basket was only 844 Forints.
This year, such extremes were not observed, as the most expensive basket cost 1,630.00 forints more than the previous year, and even the cheapest saw a price increase of 1,284.00 forints.
Compared to the last two Christmas seasons, there has been a catastrophic price increase, with the price of daily consumables in hypermarkets rising by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, in turn, does not necessarily corroborate the data from the Central Statistical Office of Hungary: for some basic foodstuffs, the Statistical Office found inflation of more than 30% over a 12-month period.
In addition to flour, eggs are about the same.)
However, if you take a look at the "Napi" shopping cart, this seems almost impossible with the latter, as the price level of the product, which was already expensive last year, has risen by barely more than 10 percent even in the worst case scenario.
Obviously, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers - after all, they have been able to pass on the drastic price increase to the multinationals.
In the golden trading triangle, the hypermarkets do not complain; good years are constantly reported.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores no longer look at the prices.
Large quantities are purchased from everything, durable food is shipped over the counter in pallets.
On Wednesday morning, there were endless queues at the checkout in all three department stores when suddenly the number of customers exploded.
However, the country reports a lower customer frequency, so that many multinationals complain to pollsters that they cannot even achieve the planned turnover, not only for food, but also for sustainable consumer goods.
In many places there is a saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overcrowding of staff - these are all factors that are not conducive to containing infections, according to the chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places, savings are also being made on disinfectants.
Recently, a MRSA infection was diagnosed in the Traumatology Department of the János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection here.
The injured man in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but shortly afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection. Since then, an important operation could not be carried out because of the bacterium that is still present in the patient's body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1,094 infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System from hospitals, according to Karolina Böröcz, senior physician at the National Center for Epidemiology.
So many multi-drug-resistant infections have certainly been recorded in hospitals, but the number is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, Staphylococcus aureus, which is resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their noses without causing disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics and are easily cured.
However, if the remedies are overdosed or improperly applied, the well-responding bacteria develop into antibiotic-resistant bacteria, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
These bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis, especially in patients with weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune systems, but also in older patients or patients with low body weight.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the daily routine of the hospital.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, nurses wear rubber gloves and masks during care, and we have the necessary antibiotics for treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, the patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, however, the currently prevailing conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for the control of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the admitted patients and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not as common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there is no subsidy from the state health insurance fund for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light if the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological studies are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always followed by hospitals.
According to Karolina Böröcz, microbiological sampling is even rarer among outpatients or primary care patients.
It is saved with the disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted from one patient to another by nursing staff.
Precisely for this reason, hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also considerable shortcomings in this area in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, the rooms are often overcrowded, with beds lined up next to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 metres between them.
Unfortunately, as Karolina Böröcz further points out, in the less well-off hospitals, savings are even being made on disinfectants, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that almost encourage the development of infections.
According to Karolina Böröcz, infections of this kind are demonstrably far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped if these protective measures are adhered to.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs for health insurance companies, therefore they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention and control of MRSA was included in the government programme.
According to the first signs, the program is successful - as published data prove, the tendency of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
Death row police chief wasn't drunk
In the case of the fatal car accident caused by the police chief of the XXII. District, the official report is now available.
The now resigned police chief of the XXII district, who killed a pedestrian in a car accident on Tuesday, was neither drunk nor under the influence of drugs, Attila Morvai, the spokesman of the Budapest Chief Public Prosecutor's Office, said on Friday after the official report on the case was presented.
The report confirmed the results of the initial investigation, according to which the police chief had not consumed alcohol before getting behind the wheel.
The former police chief turned into Kossuth Lajos Street in the XXII district in his own car and ran over a 55-year-old man who was crossing the street at an unmarked place.
(According to the StVO, however, this is not a mitigating circumstance - the driver, even if pedestrians do not cross the road at the zebra crossing, has second place.)
The pedestrian succumbed to his injuries after being taken to hospital.
According to police reports, the driver suffered a shock, then resigned and asked to retire.
The Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office has opened its investigation into the incident.
In addition, Attila Morvai mentioned that the former police chief had cooperated with investigators from the beginning.
A further EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements worth a total of EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday for education, transport and environmental infrastructure and the energy sector.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental projects implemented with grants from the Cohesion Fund. The EUR 100 million loan agreement was signed earlier and the current agreement covers the use of the EUR 200 million lent.
The sum of €150 million agreed in the loan contract will also be used for the budgetary financing of education projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary for this purpose; the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the context of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the parties have signed an agreement for EUR 50 million, which will mainly go to research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
Subway line 4 was also discussed at the meeting.
It was agreed that once Hungary had clarified the details of the metro financing with the EU, the original contract and possible modifications would be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary with a total value of EUR 8.4 billion.
The loan interest is linked to EURIBOR, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, free of commission.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe is paying close attention to the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who is buying in what is still the cheapest market in the EU, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re / Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most sought-after place for property purchases in Eastern Europe, with affordable ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa, Albena, the "Gold Coast," the "Sun Coast," and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik is also increasingly in demand.
According to the estimates of Re / Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will sooner or later attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and the extremely favorable area of Ruse is also seeing more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offers the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfers "paradise, attracting tourists not only in summer and winter but also in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already shopping on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying real estate in Bulgaria are also seeking to change their way of life.
The majority of buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while the Black Sea and ski resorts are predominantly Russian buyers.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgy Yankov, Regional Director of Re / Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle either buy revitalised properties for 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connections and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are very important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
In the second category belong those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of businessmen who invest with the aim of adding value in the medium to long term.
Properties in the capital, meanwhile, are becoming more expensive all the time, driven by ever-growing demand.
Within the EU, property prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but over the past five years there has been an annual increase of 21 percent.
House price inflation far outstrips wage increases.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As announced by Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a heated debate going on between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but it would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
The other big question at the conference is whether the industrialised countries are prepared to support the developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement has also been reached on assistance to developing countries.
The Adaptation Fund under the Kyoto Protocol will be administered by a 16-member council, probably at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), according to the "Piac és Profit."
Hungary's six percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, speaking on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's ambition to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (compared to 1990 levels), regardless of whether the "post-2012 agreement" is successful or not. Indeed, the Union would be ready to commit to a 30% reduction provided that other major industrialised countries of the world, or developing countries, are also prepared to fulfil their obligations in a strong and responsible manner.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the target of the countries that had acceded to the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its 15 member states at the time, had already committed itself to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a target the country will certainly meet, according to the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be ready within two years, otherwise it would surely not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction plans laid down in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed by another international emissions reduction scheme, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the UN's Nobel Peace Prize-winning scientific climate change committee, in its latest report.
This would delay emission reductions and increase the Earth's average temperature by more than 2 ° C, with extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British Army advertises on YouTube
British Army units have posted footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video portal in a bid to boost its popularity.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of anti-Taliban operations online since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The footage, shot with miniature cameras attached to helmets, is checked at the Kandahar air base and then sent to London, where it is posted on the internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, and their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces (MNFI) based in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Operations in Afghanistan
The Air Force originally released the videos with the goal of recruiting soldiers, and the Defense Department says the posts also serve the purpose of informing the public about the actual goals of foreign deployments.
Defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC that propaganda of this kind is almost free of charge compared to traditional television commercials, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message, because they confirm in their own way the raison d "être of the military measures adopted by the government.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur recordings that, in addition to the carefully edited, censored recordings, also make it onto the net - such as those showing the deaths of soldiers: the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films only talk about the losses, but do not show the bloody sides of the war.
Incidentally, numerous videos shot in action have already been uploaded to the platform from the theatres of war in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British have only recently discovered this "genre."
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army," in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less lifelike simulation.
Christmas Party with Tombola and Pogache in the Ministries
Labour Minister Mónika Lamperth is by no means squeamish: instead of a Christmas party, she is organising a work conference at which her staff can round off the year 2007 with coffee and pogatsch.
Some ministries celebrate with live music, others conjure up the Christmas spirit with a raffle or a toast to the hearts of civil servants.
Party, Christmas spirit, concerts and buffet - that's how the power celebrates.
Christmas fever has already hit the offices.
The biggest Christmas party of any ministry this year will be held at the Ministry of Defence, but the ministry's staff are not expected to attend.
At the "Orphan Christmas Celebration," children are presented with gifts from fallen soldiers, at the "Mission Celebration," family members of soldiers currently stationed abroad are entertained, but there is also a reception for the press.
The department is allocating around 25 million euros for the festivities.
Compared to other portfolios, the National Development Agency (NFÜ) and the Ministry of Economy and Transport are over the top.
The 4.32 million forint Christmas party of the Ministry of Economy will be held in the House of the Future, about 350 of the 600 employees are expected.
While the focus of the festivities will be on Christmas, there will also be live acts and a raffle.
The National Agency for Development (NFÜ) held its 4.7 million forint Christmas party on Wednesday in the House of the National Council of Justice (OIT), with concerts and a banquet.
The hall rent amounted to 1 Mio Forint, the rest was spent for the more than 400 invited guests.
According to our information, a branch of NFÜ is also invited to another Christmas party organised by the Hungarian Economic Development Centre (MAG Zrt) with EU funds.
The building of the Comedy Theatre ("Vígszínház") was rented for the celebration.
MAG Zrt has not confirmed this information, as we have not reached those responsible.
Why the suit?
The OIT building was open not only to NFÜ guests, but also to the Ministry of Justice and Police, which held the Lucia Ball there instead of a Christmas party on 7 December.
They did not have to pay rent to the OIT to use the premises.
About 500 visitors came to the ball.
The festivities were opened with a speech by the Minister, after the dinner there was live music to dance.
When asked by [source], they said: 'There was no obligation on the ball to wear a ball gown or suit.'
The ministries of Health, Labour and Local Government are each preparing for a puritanical celebration.
The Ministry of Health organises the celebration for employees in their own homes for around 400,000 HUF.
Employment Minister Mónika Lamperth is not officially inviting her staff to a Christmas party, but to a conference at the end of the year.
According to the press department, about 180 guests are expected to be treated to coffee and pogatsche, so the celebration is expected to be 350,000 forints.
Self-Government Minister Gordon Bajnai and his colleagues will simply toast in the auditorium of the ministry.
The Ministry of Finance (PM) is hosting a Christmas party in its own ballroom, where 436 employees are expected to attend.
The expenditure was calculated at 2,500 forints per capita - for this money there is a buffet reception followed by a toast.
Since the beginning of the term of János Veres, the PM's staff celebrate in this way every year.
However, there will be no real party atmosphere - not only because of the official speech of the minister, but also because the party has been scheduled for the afternoon.
The Ministry of Agriculture is hosting a New Year's reception on 20 January, but the ministry's Christmas party is cancelled this time.
One hundred guests are invited to the Vajdahunyad Castle in the city park ("Városliget"); according to information provided by the resort, the expenditure is 1,000 forints per guest.
As reported by the press department, it will be a very simple reception to which only foreign diplomats accredited in Hungary will be invited.
The receptions, which are held every year, traditionally begin with a short speech by the minister and end with a low-key feast.
As the corresponding press offices report on [origo] request, there will be no Christmas party at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs or the Ministry of Education.
When asked about the costs of the Christmas party, the press department of the Ministry of the Environment could not provide any information.
In any case, more than 400 guests were invited to the celebration, which is being held in the Museum of Applied Arts.
More and more forces mobilized for giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Trade Union Federation will form their coordinating committee on Friday for the indefinite strike starting on Monday.
A large protest meeting will be held on Saturday, and on Monday - the day of the referendum on the health insurance law - the work stoppage will begin.
Considerable disruption is expected due to strikes, as rail services are almost completely suspended, and Budapest's public transport companies (BKV) are also on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of Monday's strike will be jointly announced by the league and the union federation on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee will also be established, which will be responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
A large protest meeting will be held on Saturday and, from Monday, all organisations that have joined the strike will cease work indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike that began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the health insurance law was not defined.
If the National Council does not adopt the Health Insurance Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet to discuss how to proceed.
Due to the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that the vote on the health insurance law will not take place until later in the evening, or even at midnight.
The strikes, which will begin on Monday, will cause significant disruption to services: the railway workers will be suspended indefinitely, and in the morning the majority of public transport and more than half of Volán companies will be shut down.
At the same time, there will be one-way motorway closures in many places.
The call for a strike has been followed by numerous unions and civil organizations - the list of participants is updated regularly on the league's website.
Some organisations have announced strikes for an indefinite period, while others are planning temporary stoppages.
Until Thursday afternoon, no agreement could be reached between the Hungarian Railways MÁV and the Free Union of Railway Workers VDSZSZ on adequate services, even though more and more people travel by train around the Christmas holidays.
According to reports so far, strikes are taking place at BKV from the start of operations until 1 p.m., at Budapest Airport between 7 and 9 a.m., the LIGA unions for electricity and heat energy are suspending their work for four hours, and the teachers "union and the Democratic Union of Teachers have called for 2 and 2-8 hours strikes respectively.
The Hungarian Medical Association is on strike at different times throughout the country, the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organisation of the SZEF, the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraw the health insurance reform bill and propose a new conception of social discourse.
The second demand concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which is due from next year.
Demand number three is that beneficiaries should be able to access the early retirement system before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which belongs to the League of Trade Unions, did not accept the offer made by the Ministry of Transport concerning the secondary lines and is now calling for a new approach.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases sovereign risk
According to Political Capital's Risk Analysis Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, created this August with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, have increased the risk to Hungary and the region in several respects.
Among other things, the Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states that, in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "aggravation of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy populations in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term."
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which presumably aims at provoking such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of political leaders: "Public figures have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups, who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary conflict."
It is thought that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, encourage extremism, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard have "significantly damaged Hungary's image abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity," not least thanks to the enormous attention from the domestic and foreign media.
We remember that since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been on a steady upswing, so that since summer 2007 several organizations calling themselves the "National Self-Defense Association" have been founded.
"What these groups have in common is that they each define themselves as a civil organisation, while openly bragging about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (civil protection, national defence, law and order), citing the unfitness of the police, the army or the state itself," it said.
Furthermore, all this is done according to the method which attempts to disguise as a bourgeois initiative various political aspirations based on the political and party disillusionment of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association does not only serve to circumvent the legal hurdles that may arise in the course of registration with the court - it is also a political strategy.
As the analysis shows, the activities of the Hungarian Guard also constitute a risk-enhancing factor for relations with neighbouring states.
In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring states, and some ultra-nationalist politicians in certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as confirmation of their own anti-Hungary policy.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region, "it said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Central-Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has increased.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose creation was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the emergence of the Bulgarian Guard were the mass Roma evictions, which took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Polyana).
The BNU immediately took the events as the reason for the creation of the National Guard, arguing that the goal of the organization was "national protection."
According to them, a real "gypsy terror" has been noticeable in Bulgaria over the past 17 years, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent - according to Political Capital.
Furthermore, the initiative would have triggered a fierce debate among the Bulgarian public.
