Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, public holidays are strictly regulated by law, so the practice of rescheduling working days around public holidays has now become established, but the coming year will bring us fewer such days.
In the EU and America, too, "holiday" is a different term.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and non-working days.
Days off work are usually church holidays, or are associated with important historical events.
For example, we also celebrate the New Year: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone so that New Year's Eve revellers can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen public holidays.
The national holidays are 15 March, which commemorates the revolution of 1848, and 23 October, which commemorates the revolution of 1956.
On 20 August the founding of the state will be celebrated, on 1 May work will be celebrated, and on 1 and 2 November we will commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two public holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "shifting the working day" has proven effective in cases where we would work only one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the long weekends, however, is that we have to work or go to school on the Saturdays before that.
When this day, which falls before or after the public holiday, should finally be processed has been determined for many years by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants alike.
Only companies and institutions in which operations continue without interruption, including on public holidays, are excluded.
This year, the working regulations are only a little confused by the holidays at the end of the year: From December 24, life in this country will come to a virtual standstill, as most people take time off for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the holiday that has been specially reserved for them.
Next year, there will be more public holidays in the middle of the week or at the end of the week, so there will be less rescheduling of working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around Labor Day, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday 26 April will be a working day, so that Friday 2 May will be a day of rest.
The second rescheduling is related to the public holiday on 23 October: on Saturday 18 October, it will be necessary to work through Friday 24 October in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be completely dominated by the holidays, as from 24 December everything will stand still, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six chilling little things to annoy work colleagues
E-mails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice: they bring "color" to everyday life at the workplace.
The only question is whether one gets used to these small inconveniences, or one better rises to the challenge and tries to consciously avoid these ambiguous, for other annoying situations.
Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called" - says a colleague.
That you missed a meeting as a result?
At best, you regret it and try to make amends by perhaps calling the marketing department and confessing remorsefully that you forgot to deliver the message (this is the less common method).
More often than not, the matter is dismissed with an apology.
Before you become embroiled in embarrassing excuses, consider how you can cause your colleagues truly unpleasant moments and try to consciously avoid these situations.
Something borrowed that doesn't belong to you?
There's hardly anything more annoying than reaching for a document, office supplies, or phone, but it's not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - is it gone this morning?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague's desk?
We should not borrow anything from colleagues without asking questions, because they are right to be angry when they see that something has gone wrong.
So, don't put envelopes or Post-it notes from the office in your pocket, because it could hit you: no more when you really need them.
Gossip about colleagues "private lives?
There is no effective means of stopping a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who did what with whom?
Where and why?
If possible, one should not bind the information (or assumptions) about the private lives of colleagues to the nose of everyone!
And if someone does open up and reveal his innermost secret to us, we should not abuse this trust!
It is best to be silent like a grave, rather than aligning those who are not present, even if others know about your colleague's problems.
Reported ill for no reason?
When you call the office to report that you are ill, citing excruciating headaches, because you are feeling unwell, or just want to rest, you should be clear about one thing: your own work, non-postponable tasks, projects with fixed deadlines must now be done by your colleagues instead of yourself.
So don't hold your colleagues in contempt!
If you know the day before that you won't make it to the office the next day, or that something might happen in between so you have to stay at home, you should report it in good time so that neither your colleagues nor your boss are unexpectedly confronted with your absence.
Giggling, Phone, Phone
You are immersed in your work, but are you suddenly disturbed by the loud giggles of your colleagues?
Inadvertently overheard a phone conversation that should not have been heard?
One should not annoy colleagues with buzzing, singing, loud conversations (which one leads over their heads), stomping, constant cursing or grumbling.
All this can be very disturbing, even if they are not engrossed in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Is it always the other's fault?
If a project is not completed on time, if you forgot to send an important letter or important news, you should not blame others for your forgetfulness!
If possible, one should not make excuses for the chaos in the office or the noisy colleagues!
It is best to acknowledge your mistakes and apologise if others have been affected!
The question of how to make up for the mistake, or how to make up for the omission, is all too pertinent!
In the office - a feeling like at home?
Tracksuit bottoms and slippers: Comfortable at home, but has lost nothing in the office!
Not even then should one dress so casually, if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect your colleagues as well as yourself to the extent that you dress appropriately in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
Want to do it for everyone - or how to become uninteresting to others
Stop and go traffic, the car in the middle of the morning traffic jam.
A strange melody rings out from the radio: the sound of a violin paired with electronic effects.
I turn up the volume.
