The singer György Ligeti, who lives in England and works with the band "The Puzzle," introduced himself with these songs at the premiere at Millenáris.
One song from the album even made it to the radio hit - the mr2 Petőfi, which broadcasts pop music from early to late, successively catches the listeners "eye with the number" Wings of Love, "which was recorded with the participation of six local singers (" Underground Divas ").
All right then (?).
The hvg.hu has contacted Balázs Zságer.
hvg.hu: This new hit raises the question: To what extent does your music remain the preserve of a certain layer?
Balázs Zságer: The term "stratified music" doesn't really mean much to me.
In my opinion, there are two castes in pop music, not mainstream and underground, or alternative and pop, but commercial and honest.
Even so-called alternative or underground music can be shallow and meaningless, but they can also only be produced for sale, which makes them commercial music.
Even a good pop number can come from an honest motive.
The receptivity of the listener also works according to this principle, independent of languages and national borders.
hvg.hu: Do you see a difference in the openness of Hungarian and foreign audiences towards your music?
For example: In foreign countries, especially in the west of us, pop music has a larger tradition.
Not only teenagers or Twens go to concerts, but also the older audience.
They pay much more attention to the trends in pop music that are happening around them, because they also consider them to be part of contemporary culture.
hvg.hu: What is the role of the audience in your work?
Is it important who, where, how many people listen to your music?
B. Zs.: Of course it is a good feeling to see that more and more people come to our concerts.
But we never composed for the market.
For us, music is not created to serve a purpose, but for a specific reason.
The role of the audience is mostly noticeable at the concerts, where there is already a mutual interaction, but this in turn only exists in the intangible changes of the moment.
Nevertheless, one thing struck me: If you want to please everyone, you are no longer interesting.
hvg.hu: How far would you like to follow the example of Yonderboi?
He is on the road as a soloist and has rather built his career in the West.
E.g.: We don't really go his way, apart from the fact that we always try to interpret this into our music.
We see ourselves rather as team players who trust in the musical presence of the other and let it unfold.
In the beginning, of course, comparisons between our work and that of Yonderboi were inevitable, as several of us came from his band and took a different path.
hvg.hu: In the charts of mr2 Petőfi, "Wings of Love" comes first.
Many have only heard the name Zagar in connection with this number.
Was the opening deliberately staged with a slightly more popular style in the direction of a wider audience?
E.g.: We had no plans to write a hit, which should then serve as a driving force for the album.
This song is about more than that.
It was meant to be the finale of the album, with which we wanted to resolve the orgy of sounds and the somewhat more difficult themes.
hvg.hu: How did you choose the six singers?
Why them, what was the guiding principle?
E.g.: The basic idea was to make a gospel-like choir.
Then came the idea to compose the choir from talented soloists from the local music scene.
This is how the six-member choir was created - Sena, Edina Kutzora, Judie Jay, Bori Péterfy, Enikő Hodosi [Neo], Juci Németh - which we then christened "Underground Divas."
hvg.hu: Did you want to have the song in the same way, or did the girls co-design it?
E.g.: The number has been in the instrumental version for some time, but when the material for the album was ready, we thought that this number "needs something."
The sequence of chords called for a vocal part.
I sang the melody the same night, later they learned the girls.
It all came practically straight away and frighteningly spontaneous.
I remember I was quite electrified at the time, but it took the "divas."
With my voice alone, the song would never have become so powerful.
hvg.hu: But on the record as well as at the concert one had the impression that the girls were in the background.
There is no solo part (apart from Judy Jay's short solo), they have no role of their own, sing together perfectly and are no louder than the music, so their singing is not just accompanied by the music.
They also stood at the back of the stage.
Is it intentional?
B.Zs.: The fact that they stood at the back was because of purely technical problems.
However, we deliberately did not want to give them solo roles.
The number is also about forgetting one's ego a little bit, forgetting who has come from where and where, we simply allow these particular wings, the wings of love, to lift us up.
I would like others to feel the euphoric state that we felt when the song was written.
hvg.hu: Which was the most elaborate song?
For example: In the case of musical creativity, actually none at all, there have been rather more difficult tasks in mixing.
For example in "Dorian Gray's Dilemma," in which I play a concert piano, or in "Rock'n'Roll Goes To The Girls," where the groove didn't want to work any longer, but little by little everything came together, like a puzzle.
hvg.hu: What is your favourite number from the new album?
E.g.: That constantly changes with the concerts and even now that I have "let go" of the album.
Currently it's "Prophet Is A Fool," "Escape From The Earth" and the number "Never The Same."
