Budget is through
Yes, it's done.
The state budget has been approved.
What is special about this budget?
It is the first budget this government has drafted, and it was passed without the support of the opposition by the coalition majority.
The one for the current year was approved with the support of the ČSSD (social democrats), because Minister Sobotka (from that party) had presented it, and the ČSSD could therefore not afford to reject it.
Unlike the lively debate that preceded the vote on the motion of censure against the government, nothing dramatic happened this time.
The House of Representatives quietly approved this traditionally little-noticed, yet highly significant, law.
This is somewhat paradoxical.
All governance begins and ends with the individual chapters and items of the budget, whether you like it or not.
The budget is an essential part of politics, but it is obscured by the power struggle between the government and the opposition.
This is a more rewarding subject for the media, which is why they pay more attention to it.
An argument among politicians is much more interesting to the public than sober numbers.
Under previous social democratic governments, state budgets suffered from three weak points, which the budget for 2008 cannot remedy all at once:
The first is the high proportion of expenditure that is legally obligatory, not only pensions, but also social expenditure, which was decided by the "tacit" coalition of ČSSD and KSČM (communists) last year before the elections.
The second is deficit budgetary policy as a consequence of the first weakness.
The third constraint is public finance deficits, i.e. municipal budget deficits.
The biggest risk, however, is not the government budget deficit.
This budget is public and reasonably under control.
A real time bomb, however, is the municipal budget deficit.
Many mayors, in order to tap other sources of investment besides income from taxes, levies, and bank loans, often unwittingly issued bonds that left their town halls in excessive debt.
In recent years, they have been able to repay this debt by selling en masse shares in energy and other utilities that they received from the state in the course of privatization.
Now that source has already dried up.
Insofar as we adhere only to official and verifiable facts, we note that:
For several years now, our economy, like the rest of the world, has been going through a period of growth of which the ČSSD prides itself ceaselessly.
This was a unique opportunity for their governments to put their public finances in order.
Instead, these governments owed the state even more.
Other countries, with a few exceptions such as Hungary, Albania, Pakistan or Egypt, have managed much more sensibly than our republic.
This is a huge disgrace, largely attributable to the previous governments.
We are one of the countries that are least at risk of poverty on a global scale.
That is why there is no need for massive social programmes, which, unfortunately, have been unnecessarily inflated on a gigantic scale in recent years.
Although we have managed to eliminate some of the nonsensical populist expenditure adopted this year before the elections, it is clear that unless there is a postponement of the retirement age and pension reform in the near future, practically all politics in this country will end and, whoever is in power, he will be left with nothing but pure administration.
It is only a slight exaggeration to say that ruling politicians then become civil servants who mechanically allocate most of the tax revenue to pensions and social expenditure.
This is why this year's budget cannot be a revolution; it can only stop ordinary expenditure being squeezed out by compulsory expenditure.
The deficit of SEK 70 billion planned for 2008 would be superfluous if previous governments had not spent what they could in the last ten years.
If we do not really want ruling politicians to become mere administrative officials, then we must be patient and wish this not too strong coalition government, which is aware, however, that the state can only spend as much as it is able to collect in taxes and fees, peace of mind as it prepares further reform legislation.
Only these will allow a gradual implementation of a balanced state budget.
