Integration of Slovak pupils in UK schools fails
British schools are seeing an increase in the number of children from Eastern European countries, raising fears among locals about the future development of the local education system.
The integration of Eastern Europeans has so far encountered a number of obstacles.
British schools are even seeing cases where disputes between immigrants and the children of the original inhabitants are increasing in violence.
The problem of integrating children from Eastern Europe into British schools is aptly illustrated by the case of North Kent, where disputes between locals and Slovak immigrants are gradually increasing.
Squabbles, bullying and scuffles among pupils have spread to relationships between parents.
