Cuba - most beautiful island of the Caribbean
For visitors, it really is an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, it will come true if you only choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a calm sea like a pond.
Palm trees and all inclusive with waiters serving pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
But there is only one island where you will find much more, and that island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place ever seen by a human eye.
Havana was once a warehouse or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had looted in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American epoch.
The Hotel Nacional was founded at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the heads of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the USA (especially during Prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were:
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, skyscrapers grew, and the wide boulevards were crossed by cars, which were among the cult symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of showbusiness and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Havana Bodeguita.
At the bar of the Hotel Nacional, cocktails can be mixed to your liking.
And the cult cars of the fifties still drive around Havana today, because the once imported schigulis and fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
Havana, especially its oldest part, may have been very run-down, nowhere in the vicinity you will find so many wonderful colonial sights as just here.
Other places are being cleaned up, such as Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, this development has been given the green light.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have sprung up not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín, and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a quirk that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
Sugar cane from remote plantations brought narrow-gauge steam and diesel trains to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see cute and fully functioning locomotives, whose contemporaries have long since been in the museum elsewhere.

The majority of visitors to Cuba do not miss the most important places.
You don't have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail anymore.
It is worth mentioning that the aforementioned Hemingway estate houses a museum, which should not be missed by anyone who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The Mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, and fertile soil accumulates in their cavities, through which even weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet it when you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was shot there.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
The trade in slaves and sugar brought her fame and wealth.
The wealth was embodied in the pretty beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, situated between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that even in the 1950s there was no road connecting the area to the rest of the country.
This isolation contributed to the fact that it went unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was demolished, everyone was happy that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than an afternoon in Trinidad, it is worth visiting interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancon beach or the Valley of the Sugar Factories.
In the evening, one should then go to the Casa de la Música, which comes alive after dark, and where the music is not silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the far east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
Surely this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading from Guantánamo have to cross high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape barely touched by human intervention.
Thanks to the unspoilt nature there, UNESCO included this eastern outpost of Cuba in its World Heritage List.
This is where the best chocolate is made, where the cross of Columbus is displayed in the church (in fact, it was made about a hundred years after Columbus sailed), and from the hill where the former castle, now the Hotel El Castillo, stands, several table mountains can be seen, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
Many pages could be written about coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patron saint Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion professed by the descendants of slaves.
But, as they say, it's better to see things with your own eyes.
Allies in Afghanistan are passive, Americans say.
According to the United States, too few troops and the lack of necessary equipment are affecting the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
NATO should, in the words of Defense Secretary Robert Gates, draw up a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going according to their ideas, the representatives of the countries that have units stationed in the south of the country agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland.
In addition to growing Taliban resistance, the eight participating states are also discussing further coordination plans among the allies.
While the United States, through its Secretary of Defense, Robert Gates, called on NATO units to be more active, Britain sees the priority in strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and stepping up development assistance.
"There is progress in Afghanistan, but military power can only be part of the solution.
