Government debt set to soar to £1trillion in 2009
Each Czechs has a national debt of CZK 84,000.
Total debt rose to 842.7 billion kronor by the end of September.
The government had planned to borrow $159.2 billion this year.
At the beginning of December, however, the ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion, thanks to the better development of state budgetary policy.
The public debt of the Czech Republic rose to 842.7 billion kronor by the end of September.
As a result, they rose by 40.2 billion in the first nine months of this year.
Since June, however, they have fallen by $13.4 billion.
The Treasury confirmed its figures on the national debt at the start of October.
For every Czech there is a debt of 84000 kronor.
Over the whole of last year, the state was indebted by more than 111 billion kronor.
"So far, it seems that, thanks to the lower deficit for next year, we may not exceed the one trillion kroner mark until 2009.
Next year, the debt should be between 900 billion and 1 trillion kroner, "David Marek, an analyst at Patria Finance, told iHNed.cz.
Vladimír Pikora, analyst at Next Finance, takes a similar view: "We could exceed one trillion in the course of 2009.
Exactly when depends on the next budget, which we do not yet know.
If it turns out that the situation on the political stage is changing, and politicians are willing to save more, it could take until 2010.
But I don't expect that to change, "he said.
Debt Growing
The national debt stems from the debts of the state government and, above all, from the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
The public debt is financed by Treasury bills, government bonds, direct bonds or, for example, bonds issued by the European Investment Bank.
Domestic public debt has now risen to 719.4 billion kronor this year.
The foreign debt of the state meanwhile rose by 1.7 billion kroner to 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable public debt reached 803.3 billion kroner at the end of September and has fallen by 13.7 billion kroner since June.
The average maturity of government debt rose to 6.5 years.
Total debt rose 13 percent over the year from the first to the third quarter, which is really a lot given how well the economy is doing.
It is interesting to note that the growth is particularly noticeable in bonds, where the increase is 20%.
It is bad that debt is rising, but on the other hand it shows that something can be done even before the pension reform comes, "Pikora commented on the data.
Better than expected
According to the financing strategy and the management of the national debt for 2007, the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion kronor this year.
At the beginning of December, however, the ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion kronor thanks to the better development of the state's budgetary policy.
This amount is mainly due to the state budget deficit, which is expected to reach 76 billion kronor this year instead of the estimated 91.3 billion kronor.
There is also a maximum budget for the Consolidation Agency of CZK 13.3 billion, a reserve of CZK 10 billion to pay pensions, the financing of public bonds of CZK 43 billion and installments for bonds with the European Investment Bank of CZK 1.8 billion.
She was brought before a court in Khartoum today for giving a name to a teddy bear.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been accused of insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening to 15 days imprisonment and subsequent deportation.
The British woman has been accused of allowing six to seven-year-old pupils to give a teddy bear the name Mahomet, despite the fact that any depiction of the Islamic prophet is forbidden.
She deserved to be flogged.
After parents of students complained several times to the Sudanese Ministry of Education, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at Unity High School in Khartoum, was apprehended at her home on Sunday and charged under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code with insulting Islam.
In fact, the affair began in September, when the teacher asked her six to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the classroom teddy bear.
The children suggest eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, school principal Robert Boules said.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Sure, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all a very common first name in Sudan.
The children then created a book for the class, with a photo of the bear on it and the caption: 'My name is Mohammed.'
The bear itself did not carry a sign with that name, but the problem is quite simple: the depiction of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said that he knew her well and that she had never done anything to offend a religious faith, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion it was just an innocent mistake.
An opinion shared by many of the teacher's students, who describe her as very attentive to her students and as a person who never talks about religion in class.
Consider that the first name Mohammed is also the second most common middle name in Britain, with 14 different spellings in English.
This first name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of homage to the Prophet (it is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
At the last negotiating session in Vienna on Wednesday, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
The End of the Failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo concluded a sixth and final discussion session Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without being able to overcome their controversies over the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties could not reach an agreement on the status," European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region is at stake, its American counterpart Frank Wilsner called on Belgrade and Pristina to fulfill their obligations to maintain peace and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No violence is expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult period, he added, indicating that there are clearly tensions.
Conciliation ended on 10 December
The mediators of the troika, which brings together the European Union, the USA and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the province, which is inhabited by 90% Albanian speakers, could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and the Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by 10 December.
The Baden talks, near Vienna, were the sixth and final negotiating session since the troika received a mandate from the UN last August to mediate.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mission to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked the approval of Kosovo's independence at the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond that end date.
Russia has been and remains an advocate of a negotiated solution, an amicable solution, Botsane-Khartchenko said.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After eight years of UN administration in Kosovo, Western countries see independence under EU supervision as the only solution with a future.
Pristina is prepared to announce them unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in their favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached, announced the President of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, in the hotel in Baden, where, since Monday, these last-chance negotiations have been held.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regret.
However, he added that the plan for autonomy proposed by Belgrade belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations.
Domino's effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, said that a compromise should always be sought and warned the Kosovo Albanian majority against the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence by the province.
Belgrade says it particularly fears a "domino effect" in a region so weakened by the independence wars of the 1990s.
For Serbia, this does not mean that compromise is impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision would be taken solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally has veto power.
The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word
Only a decision from the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia, stated Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica.
These negotiations took two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.
Fatmir Sejdiu told reporters that the Kosovo parliament would have the final say on the status, adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking population would be made in coordination with Western countries.
