A heavy memory
After being kept confidential for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed over a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be consulted until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individually and by name, i.e. on request of a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven states entrusted with its administration - including Germany, France, Israel and the USA - agreed in May 2006 to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to carry out research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of the forced laborers, explains Reto Meister, director of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the delicate nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of some deportation victims.
The prisoner lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo were compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labor, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal enquiries.
Nevertheless, a part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One must not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, said Pr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Centre for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
