Congress approves the MIFID directive, which entered into force on 1 November.
Parallel to the parliamentary drafting, which concluded its session today with the Congressional resolution in the Senate on the amendments / supplements to the project, the government published the provisions resulting from the new law with the intention of enabling the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
Representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of the members of Congress and the Senate, who in their negotiations and votes had pursued the goal of establishing the best possible regulation, which guarantees the safety of investors and regulates the individual business activities, in order to guarantee generally efficient market operations.
MIFID, which redefines the rules governing investment services, aims, in addition to the modernisation of financial markets, to improve investor protection, increase the supervisory role of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive will make it possible to offer financial advice to specialised firms as well as to natural or legal persons and will also contribute to the establishment of new financial services companies (ESIS), the advisory firms joining forces with investment and intermediary companies in securities.
It also expands the number of systems for executing financial transactions, adding to regulated circulation markets the multilateral systems of securities transactions and the systems for internationalising trade orders, which would eventually compete with current economic operators.
The law obliges investment companies to disclose to the market the focus of their company profile, the confrontation and ways of dealing with risks, and to register all projects carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV's control task.
The Congressional Economic Commission made further amendments in retrospect, and the decision that the securities must now be considered complex financial instruments due to their high level of risk for the investor was confirmed by the US mortgage and banking crisis.
It also took advantage of the entry into force of the directive on the legal limitation of the work of graduated economists, 30 years after the adoption in 1977 of the regulation restricting the work reserved for economists.
The Senate, for its part, determined new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the business mediator, who works on behalf of others, does not require authorization from the CNMV and can offer his services for the commercialization of products and customer acquisition simultaneously to several investment companies.
