Fresh fears over gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is brewing between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of Russia's natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) pass through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for the natural gas, it will be charged higher transit fees by Russia.
A previous conflict between the two states last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine must be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% more for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," Ukraine's Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
"Changing gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments about the level of transit charges [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which pushed up prices dramatically.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own reserves with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish NHS needs to improve checks on criminal records for workers from outside Europe, a member of the watchdog has said.
The recommendation from chief financial officer Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was linked to the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also raised concerns that the Scottish NHS does not have a clear idea of the number of foreign staff it employs.
But his report pointed out that other key checks were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The chief financial controller was investigating staff recruited outside the European Economic Area in the wake of the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an SUV drove through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at the Old Bailey in October and has been charged in connection with the alleged car bomb attack in Britain.
The NHS is expected to carry out pre-employment checks on foreign staff to ensure they have the qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK.
Although health boards use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside the UK.
The chief auditor's report now says, among other recommendations, that the board should adopt guidelines from the Criminal Records Review Act, which helps employers carry out inspections in different countries.
"Although we found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, they were not carried out routinely," the report said.
Black said Scottish health boards would follow their screening guidelines to a large extent before hiring, but added: "Our report identifies areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information is available on the number of overseas health workers."
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that pre-recruitment investigations would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report states that current pre-appointment testing by NHS Scotland is working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
Scottish health boards say they currently have 1,161 foreign staff, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the Financial Conduct Authority warned that the number was likely to be higher, in part because boards were struggling to identify those employees who were on indefinite leave.
The investigation also found that established control procedures had largely been followed by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
These include passport, work permit and qualification checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidance on pre-employment checks for foreign staff in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was keen to carry out this work in the light of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
She added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with health boards, would take into account the report's recommendations and ensure that best practice was reflected in updated guidance on pre-employment screening for all staff - including those from abroad - which is due to be published next month.
