The climate on Venus could offer a glimpse of the future of Earth
Venus may once have been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from an orbiting European spacecraft show that the planet resembles a distant twin of Earth even more than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor of Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, Venus would have had conditions very similar to those on Earth and could even have been habitable, scientists believe today.
But because of the unchecked carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation, and a slower pace of rotation, Venus took a very different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a sobering look at how the Earth could evolve in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, from the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: 'It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar.'
