All still open
Mitt Romney said he doesn't think it's worthy of a presidential candidate to be questioned by a snowman.
Still, the Republican nominee for president eventually agreed to face a debate on YouTube in which ordinary voters videotape and submit questions to send to the candidate.
None of the questions raised on Wednesday night, November 28, were as ridiculous as the snowman interviewing Democrats about global warming in the other party's YouTube debate.
But the questions, and the answers, this time accurately reflected the state of the Republican Party heading into next year's elections.
It is not known how the producers of CNN, who co-sponsored the debate, chose the aspiring candidate to show YouTube clips.
But in the first half-hour of the debate, the longest devoted to a single issue, immigration took center stage.
The issue is one of the most potent topics for Republicans.
CNN asked a group of undecided voters to serve up a dial when they heard things they liked: The television station noted spikes in approval as the candidates talked sternly about the boundaries.
The sharpest and longest exchange of the evening was between Rudy Giuliani, the national front-runner, and Romney, who has moved ahead in crucial Iowa and New Hampshire polls.
Giuliani is trying to shake off a reputation for being soft on illegal immigration when he was mayor of New York.
He attacked Romney, accusing the former Massachusetts governor of hiring illegal immigrants to work at his home.
The two clashed particularly fiercely when questioners asked whether any of the candidates would support an "amnesty" (giving illegals regular status and the option of citizenship).
Minor candidates, such as Duncan Hunter, a California congressman, and Tom Tancredo, a Colorado congressman, managed to catch up on the issue.
Neither man has a serious chance of winning the nomination, but both remain in the race, perhaps because they hit the immigration picket earlier and harder than others.
On immigration, at least, the candidates broadly share the same views: tighter borders, intolerance of illegal migrants.
This issue, along with fears about toxic toys from China or other concerns about the rest of the world, helps Republicans forget or minimize the differences between liberals and Christian conservatives.
But the debate clearly became problematic as other issues were raised.
Mr. Giuliani was asked why he had supported gun restrictions in the past.
John McCain and Romney discussed whether simulated drowning should be considered torture.
One of the questioners asked if the candidates believed every word of the Bible.
This led Giuliani to argue that while the Bible was his favorite book, he might not literally believe the story of Jonah and the Whale.
Another questioner asked if Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee - now, against all expectations, in first place in a recent Iowa poll thanks to his long-standing Christian conservatism - said the death penalty was painful but necessary.
When pressed on whether Jesus would endorse them, he laughed and said Jesus was too intelligent to run for political office.
The race remains exceptionally wide open.
Huckabee's rise in Iowa coincides with Ron Paul's recent fundraising success and his thunderous applause in Wednesday's debate.
These two have sprung up out of nowhere, because the two wings of the party have not yet been able to agree on one of the better-known and more traditional candidates.
In 1980 and 2000, one candidate united the party convincingly from the outset with a winning message about America's greatness and a wink to both wings of the party.
This time, the party is divided, and the outcome is far from clear.
Labour's pain
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to fall into; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly slippery.
No titles appear to have been sold, no politician has paid Paris hotel bills, no extra-marital toes have been sucked.
But the revelation that a wealthy businessman has concealed donations to Britain's ruling Labour Party of more than 650,000 pounds ($1.3 million) over four years under other people's names, and that the party failed to report them, is something the embattled Gordon Brown would have done well without.
When, two months ago, the Prime Minister ducked the call for an election, foolishly insulting the intelligence of the British people by claiming that opinion polls had not influenced this decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly shrewd leader of the Liberal Democrats, put it, the once-feared Brown has gone from Stalin to Mr Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a troubled bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Badly thought-out proposals to change tax laws have turned business groups against the government.
The loss of 25 million people's personal data by the tax authorities exposed unimaginable administrative bottlenecks.
A trio of retired generals launched a rebellion in the House of Lords in protest at cuts to military spending: being an Armed Forces minister, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the multiple donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's general secretary (and its former performance director) has already resigned.
None of this means Brown is heading irrevocably for resignation.
Yet governments can reach a tipping point after which they feel it impossible to govern.
People neither like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he does not even need to be there for long, that delay is over: the civil service is beginning to leak; cabinet ministers are starting to talk; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In one way, Brown's position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would like to disown Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant-in-chief.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax dodgy dossiers, for example, are linked to decisions made by Brown as Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he was not directly involved in Blair's misfortunes - as with the long "money for honours" inquiry into political party funding - voters may assume he was.
Still, Brown's situation isn't quite as bad as it looks
The failings are not as terrible as the Conservatives describe them.
As with Mr. Bean, no one has died, or been robbed entirely.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown's naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: reliable, solid, and slightly brutal government.
The new fuss about political donations is a good example.
The Garboesque Abrahams, who compares his donations to his charitable gifts, says he doesn't want public recognition for his benevolence.
It may be so, but it was not for him to decide.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear, and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who run the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham's agreement but did not think it was illegal, will of course have to face some questions, as will Jon Mendlesohn, Labour's chief fundraiser, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far, Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew about the confusion, even though most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the job.
He was quick to condemn his party's violation of the law, but he diluted that resolve by reaching for a well-known tool, a committee of inquiry into the issue - led, to put it mildly, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law has been broken, it's a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr Brown needs to do, such as find a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has been vacant for six months, and move forward with sweeping reform of political party funding.
That would require Labour hardliners to work with the Conservatives and possibly abandon the special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a party colleague like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in the polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can win is through unimpeachable probity and solid competence.
Card sharks
Is America's credit card market on the verge of a credit crunch?
When there is blood in the water, it is only natural that dorsal fins twirl around excitedly.
Now that America's housing market is ailing, the predators have their sights set on the country's credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs reckon credit card losses could reach $99 billion as the contagion of underfinanced credit spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There has been an increase in both cancellations and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are either non-recoverable or more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it had taken a $1.4 billion charge from its American consumer finance arm, in part because of the weakness of credit card borrowers.
However, it is too early to panic.
Losses and delays are still low.
According to ratings agency Moody's, the third-quarter default rate of 3.89% was nearly a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can partly be explained by technical factors.
A change in America's private bankruptcy laws in 2005 led to an abrupt fall in bankruptcy filings, which in turn accounted for a large portion of card losses; the number of filings (and thus default fees) would rise again, whether or not the overall conditions for borrowers worsened.
The industry also reports solid payment rates that show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup, a research firm, reckons spending in 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct channels of infection between the housing credit crisis and the credit card market: consumers are more likely to take out credit card debt now that home loans are drying up.
Card issuers, however, look at the flow of money rather than capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower's creditworthiness.
They can even be beneficial for card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage rates decrease when the real estate is worth less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also react much more quickly and flexibly than lenders to the stormy conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should, in theory, reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
"We're not going to wake up one day and completely re-evaluate the loans," said Gary Perlin, Capital One's chief financial officer.
Even if a sudden underfunding crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are much more real.
If lower house prices and a credit squeeze push America into recession, the industry will no doubt face a grimmer future.
Keep an eye out for these shark fins.
British bankers plead guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who were due to stand trial for their role in the fraudulent scheme with Enron's former chief financial officer Andrew Fastow changed their pleas to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had originally pleaded not guilty to seven counts of wire fraud for allegedly conspiring with Fastow in a secret financial scam in 2000 to enrich himself at the expense of his employer.
The trial had been set for Jan.
But during a court hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr. each pleaded guilty to one count of fraud using telecommunications equipment.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, became known in Britain during extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, her case marks the end of an investigation launched after Enron's collapse in 2001.
The charges originally filed against them in 2002 drew Fastow's attention to the fact that he was the target of a government investigation into Enron's demise.
The indictment against the bankers - dubbed the "NatWest Three" - alleges they came to Houston in 2000 to concoct a fraudulent plot with Fastow and his former top adviser Michael Kopper.
Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partnership controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of myriad fraudulent Enron schemes that helped drag the company into the maelstrom of bankruptcy.
By early 2002, the bank had estimated the value of its stake in the subsidiary to be zero, but the three British men knew it actually had significant value.
A company controlled by Copper bought the bank's stake in the subsidiary for $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in the company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely claimed to Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its stake in the subsidiary.
But in fact, the $20 million went to British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others raked in about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in Enron's bankruptcy.
The British trio were arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence in a Louisiana federal prison.
Kopper is serving a sentence of three years and one month at a facility in Texarkana.
Each of the three men was at large on a $1 million bond that required them to live in the United States while awaiting trial.
Enron, once the nation's seventh-largest company, crumbled in bankruptcy in December 2001, after years of accounting trickery could no longer disguise billions of dollars in debt or make failing ventures seem profitable.
The collapse wiped out thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion in market value and more than $2 billion in pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the Enron collapse.
Skilling is serving a sentence of more than 24 years.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were nullified after he died last year of heart disease.
