Hopes central bank will cut interest rates lead to rise in world stock markets
Stocks jumped yesterday on both sides of the Atlantic after market hopes that the central bank will try to calm credit markets with further rate cuts were buoyed by soothing comments from the vice chairman of the US central bank.
Stock markets rose in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kahn, the number two pick of Ben Bernanke, the chairman of the central bank, said policymakers needed to respond "flexibly and pragmatically" to ongoing pressures in financial markets.
In a clear effort to calm angry markets in the face of signs of rising credit tensions, Kohn said the recent turmoil had "partially reversed some of the improvements in market functionality from late September and October."
If the heightened turbulence persists, it would raise the possibility of further tightening financial conditions for consumers and businesses, he said.
The comments were seized on by investors as a signal that the central bank is ready to step in and stabilize credit conditions with fresh capital injections into US markets and possible further interest rate cuts.
The remarks also helped to calm Wall Street in the face of more bad news from the U.S. economy, as sales of U.S. homes hit a new record low in October.
The fallout from the financial turmoil was underscored by the announcement by Bear Stearns, the investment bank, that it would eliminate 650 jobs, or 4 percent of its global workforce, in a cost-cutting move to offset heavy losses from its lost bets in the US mortgage lending sector.
Only 20 of those jobs are expected to disappear in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones industrial index jumped 331 points, or 2.55 percent, to close at 13,289.40, while the broader S & P 500 index rose 2.65 percent.
In London, the FTSE 100 index rose 165.5 points, or 2.7 per cent, to close at 6,306.2, adding more than £39bn to the value of UK stocks.
Germany's Dax index rose 2.6 percent and France's CAC40 rose 2.3 percent.
Earlier, the resurgence of credit pressure on the markets was underlined after strong demand for an auction of European Central Bank three-month guarantees granted to European commercial banks was lent at a remarkable 4.7 percent, the highest rate since April 2001.
Pressure on the Bank of England, the US Central Bank and the European Central Bank to follow suit and inject more capital into the money markets in London increased as credit tensions saw three-month "Libor" rates for lending between UK banks rise to 6.59 per cent, their highest since late September, after a steady rise since November 21.
England face decision on Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara claims
Here are two dilemmas, each almost as difficult as the other.
Who should bat at No 6 for England in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, no less relevant in a wider context than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who should make the decision?
The second question is important because David Graveney, the selectors "chairman, is here on call, at least under this particular title, to help head coach Peter Moores and captain Michael Vaughan decide, and because the table of High Morries, the England managing director, is gradually filling up with applications for national selections, if not part-time ones.
Whoever does not get the sixth bracket will be unhappy, but life is often unfair and sport undoubtedly is.
It is never easy to nail down exactly what enables a person to reach the top of their profession, while someone else never gets above the lowest rank, sometimes for lack of luck rather than ability.
It's not just in cricket where selection is difficult, where judgments are always subjective in the end.
Is it the right time for Bopara to step up?
Is it fair to Shah if he does?
The same might be asked in another area, for example, whether John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, both intelligent young executives with good degrees who know the business well, should be promoted.
Who can say what class a cricketer is, unless he is given the opportunity to swim or sink?
Of course, numbers have a big influence on decisions, but chances are they do.
Within a team, a cricketer needs to catch the captain's eye at the right time if he can take a wicket and a batsman needs to get regular opportunities on the order if he wants to make an impression as a one-day cricketer.
Catching the eyes of selectors is more complicated.
There were many who were better last season than, say, James Anderson, who looks set to play in the first Test even if Stephen Harmison declares himself healthy and bowls like the wind is blowing in the nets.
Anderson took 32 first-class wickets at 33 runs each to earn a place on this tour.
Chris Tremlett took only 29 with the same modest average but both had their highlights and are hoping for more.
Whether Shah or Bopara plays at Asgiriya Stadium can only be a matter of opinion.
The choice could decide the careers of both men, or it may just make little difference.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played in every Test and was successful in the first, taking five wickets and scoring 40 useful runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, then still struggling to cement himself, who made the breakthrough into a major Test cricketer and who, despite scoring a double hundred against Australia in Australia, is perhaps still underestimated.
It is likely that Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, after further discussion in today's nets session at Asgiriya Stadium, will follow their conservative instincts and gut instincts for Shah's greater experience of Bopara's youthful enthusiasm.
There is an argument for both.
For Shah, his scintillating and valuable 88 Test debut innings in Bombay, 43 first-class hundreds and just six from Bopara, who at 22 is seven years his junior, and an excellent record against spin balls speaks for itself.
But Shah made just ten runs in his two innings in May against West Indies in the Test at Lord's, his home ground as a Middlesex player, and this, plus his immediate rejection by the selectors when Vaughan was healthy to resume his position for the next game, appears to have taken the momentum from his batting, which was still evident in Bombay.
By contrast, the Essex all-rounder has a zest for life.
He is unfazed by anything on a cricket pitch and his attitude away from it was summed up when he knocked over a four-wheel drive vehicle in a recent exhibition for England's sponsor Volkswagen.
He suffered minor injuries and probably a shock, but the first thing he did was get his Vodafone (sponsored, of course) out and call his team-mate Alastair Cook, who had been watching it from afar, and say enthusiastically: "Did you see that?"
Bopara is a much better fielder, he bowls his middle pace with some impact here on the pitches, which seems to suit him, and beats with confidence and skill.
Choosing the right man is one thing, choosing the right time is another.
Maybe that's the real art of selection.
I'm inclined to give Bopara his chance now, which doesn't mean Shah might not do well if, as the tea set from Ceylon suggests, he's the one playing here this weekend.
Buses Bring Refugees Back to Work - and to Fight Al Qaeda
The first busloads of Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, with a stream of displaced people whose funds or visas have run out and others hoping the city will return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the rebels who had driven them from their homes.
At Mansour bus station, before 800 people arrived from Damascus in an official government convoy of a dozen buses, the terminal was busy with refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned in private transports.
"I decided to go to Syria after they killed many doctors in Baghdad," said Sabah Al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
"I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspaper, about what happened in Baghdad and how it would be safe now."
They say that the Mahdi Army has stopped killing people, "he said, referring to the Shiite militias of militant cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who has ordered his forces to withdraw.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher from the predominantly Sunni part of Amariyah, returned with his two children because he could not renew his Syrian visa and because the regime does not allow Iraqis to work.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah called him to tell him that a local, US-backed militia had helped drive al-Qaeda out of its stronghold west of the capital and urged him to return.
One of the newcomers from Jordan was the leader of a Sunni and Shiite tribe who was driven from his home in Sleikh, north of Baghdad, by a hand grenade attack after urging his fellow citizens to fight al-Qaida.
He was coming back to fight.
"Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they were starting an anti-Al Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my boys.
That's why I returned today, "said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they had been lured by the increasing calm in the capital since the U.S. troop surge and the growth of local "groups of concerned citizens" who are armed and working with the American military to defend their neighborhoods.
But more said they had been forced home by visa problems and dwindling funds in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have fled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, a 51-year-old father of three, expressed widespread suspicion among exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, had asked the Syrian government to impose visa restrictions on refugees in order to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people are believed to have fled the country's sectarian death squads.
"We were fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and the government urged Iraqis to stop giving visas to force them to return to Iraq," said the Sunni pensioner.
'I can't trust a government that supports the criminals who burned my house down after I left. '
