Venus is the hellish twin of Earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind swirls at the poles, which also occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the proof - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning flashes on Venus shoot from cloud to cloud at an altitude of around 56 kilometres, reports Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific journal "Nature."
According to the famous "primordial soup theory," lightning created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there was ever life there, it must have been in very early history," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, temperatures of 500 degrees sometimes prevail.
"Venus may be Earth's devil twin, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has embarked on such a completely different development is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as no spacecraft has traveled specifically to explore this planet since the early 1990s.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities between our neighbouring planet and Earth are greater than first thought," says Esa.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud vortex at the South Pole that rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the earthly winter hemisphere, according to a research team headed by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost as large with a diameter of 12,100 kilometres.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it rotates much more slowly around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, bears little resemblance to Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained in oceans on Earth, but was lost to space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonate rocks on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
