The prehistory is nested, a confusing concatenation of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-and-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol's permission - hundreds of Brillo cardboard boxes: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably gave permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, but these were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Eyewitnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at the time rightly went down in art and auction history as authentic Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Stockholm type."
Some of them have fetched more than $100,000 at auction.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced in Malmö until 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator at Moderna Museet, examined the six museum-owned Brillo boxes as well as three privately owned Swedish boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their chipboard was first primed and sanded off, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the chipboard with a paint roller without a primer - in addition, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York comes to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies / exhibition material."
Back in July, however, the authentication board announced it would investigate the "serious allegations" made about the soap powder boxes.
But since then, there has been an unrelenting silence.
Rebellious soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers who had barricaded themselves in a hotel in Manila and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo have given up.
He cannot be blamed for bloodshed, leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel.
Soldiers loyal to the government had earlier stormed the hotel using tear gas.
The two dozen or so soldiers had been holed up in the building for hours.
Around half of them - including Trillanes - were on trial on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003.
He used the trial to suddenly break away with around 30 sympathisers.
The military policemen who were supposed to guard him had apparently defected to him and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the ouster of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government forces cordoned off the area around the upscale hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers' actions.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
'We're calling on people to join us. '
Gen. Danilo Lim, who once commanded the elite Scout Rangers unit, said other army units would join the march soon.
Government critics had called for large demonstrations against the president on Friday.
Her government has been dogged for months by allegations of corruption.
Manila's financial district was the scene of an attempted mutiny against Arroyo by about 200 military personnel in 2003.
The uprising collapsed after barely 24 hours because of the army's refusal to join.
There have been at least seven attempted coups against democratically elected governments in the Philippines since 1986.
United Internet becomes a major shareholder in Versatel
United Internet has secured a stake of more than 20 percent in the telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, the company announced on Wednesday evening.
It now holds 20.05 percent of the share capital.
There had previously been speculation about a takeover.
One keeps the option open to increase the share of Versatel still.
The move is aimed at accelerating the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet said.
Earlier on Wednesday, speculation about a takeover had already arisen after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf-based network operator by a further 5 per cent to 15.1 per cent.
The money house holds the shares only for a third party, it was reported in the financial market.
The day before, United Internet had already acquired just under 10 percent of the mobile phone company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch has placed 17.4 million new shares with a value of 106.4 million euros.
United Internet bought 5.15 million shares for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies have entered into discussions on marketing co-operations for DSL and mobile products.
"We are strengthening our partnership," a United spokesman said.
The two companies created the MSP joint venture to acquire competitor Freenet.
For the time being, the two companies want to be satisfied with a good ten percent stake in Freenet and do not want to make use of their right to acquire a further 18.49 percent stake in Freenet, United Internet announced on Thursday.
However, the two companies kept all options open, in particular to further increase their shareholding in Freenet AG, it was reported.
Talks between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership had ended in mid-November.
The poker around Freenet, which has been going on for months and is difficult to understand, is part of the consolidation of the German telecoms market.
Freenet had 2.9 million mobile subscribers and 1.27 million DSL and full-line subscribers at the end of the third quarter.
The holding company of United Internet and Drillisch previously directly held 6.01 percent of the Freenet shares.
It has now been agreed that Drillisch will contribute a further four percent.
The right to buy the 18.49 percent stake from the investment company Vatas had already been agreed in August.
